SIMPLE: instill
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Instill
<hw>In*still"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Instilled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Instilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>instillare</ets>, <ets>instillatum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>stillare</ets> to drop, fr. <ets>stilla</ets> a drop: cf. F.
<ets>instiller</ets>. See <er>Distill</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>instil</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To drop in; to pour in drop
by drop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That starlight dews⟦br⟧
All silently their tears of love <qex>instill</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>To infuse (knowledge
or attitudes) into the mind of another, slowly or gradually; to impart
gradually; to cause to be imbibed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>How hast thou <qex>instilled</qex>⟦br⟧
Thy malice into thousands.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To infuse; impart; inspire; implant; inculcate;
insinuate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instillation</ent>⟦br⟧
